      <hedline>
        <hl1>Summer Squall in Southampton</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>William Sell letter on May 30 article holds issue of taxation without representation raised by summer residents of resort communities applies to broader issue of privatization</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The conundrum faced by property owners who can't vote (front page, May 30) is another side of the privatization movement that has been around for several years. For a time, money appeared to address issues of accountability better than voting.  Thus, schools, jails, waste removal and even policing are bought and paid for in this astonishing experiment with citizenship.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The conundrum faced by property owners who can't vote (front page, May 30) is another side of the privatization movement that has been around for several years. For a time, money appeared to address issues of accountability better than voting.  Thus, schools, jails, waste removal and even policing are bought and paid for in this astonishing experiment with citizenship.</p>
        <p>No one can be happy that the government is taxing without representation. It is a good omen that the taxed parties are now asking questions. The arena of discussion, however, is larger than summer homes.</p>
        <p>WILLIAM SELL  Milwaukee, May 30, 2000</p>
      </block>
